---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { siteConfig } from '@/data/site';

const title = 'How to Start an LLC in Florida (2026 Guide)';
const description =
  'Step-by-step guide to forming an LLC in Florida. Learn about the $125 filing fee, sunbiz.org registration, annual report requirements, and everything you need for your Florida LLC.';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#1e3a5f]/90 py-16 sm:py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 text-center sm:px-6">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white sm:text-4xl lg:text-5xl">
        How to Start an LLC in Florida
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm font-medium text-blue-200">Updated for 2026</p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-blue-100">
        Florida offers a combination of low filing fees, no state income tax, and a strong business ecosystem that makes it an excellent state for forming your LLC.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 sm:py-16">

    <!-- Quick Facts -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Florida LLC Quick Facts</h2>
        <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          {[
            { label: 'Filing Fee', value: '$125' },
            { label: 'State Agency', value: 'FL Division of Corporations' },
            { label: 'Formation Document', value: 'Articles of Organization' },
            { label: 'State Income Tax', value: 'None (personal)' },
            { label: 'Annual Report Fee', value: '$138.75' },
            { label: 'Filing Website', value: 'sunbiz.org' },
          ].map((fact) => (
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-gray-50 p-3">
              <span class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-gray-500">{fact.label}</span>
              <p class="mt-1 text-sm font-bold text-gray-900">{fact.value}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-gray-500">
          Fees and requirements shown are based on our most recent review. Always verify current information at <a href="https://dos.fl.gov/sunbiz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">sunbiz.org</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Affiliate Disclosure -->
    <div class="mb-10 rounded-xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50/50 p-4 text-xs leading-relaxed text-gray-600">
      {siteConfig.disclosureText}
    </div>

    <!-- Why Florida -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Why Form an LLC in Florida?</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          Florida is one of the fastest-growing states in the U.S. for business formation. It offers entrepreneurs several advantages that make it an attractive place to start and operate an LLC.
        </p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>No personal state income tax:</strong> Florida does not tax personal income, which means LLC members keep more of their pass-through profits.</li>
          <li><strong>Affordable filing fee:</strong> At $125, Florida's LLC filing fee is lower than many other popular business states.</li>
          <li><strong>Simple online filing:</strong> Florida's sunbiz.org platform makes it straightforward to file formation documents, search business names, and manage your annual reports online.</li>
          <li><strong>Large consumer market:</strong> With over 22 million residents and a massive tourism industry, Florida offers a vast customer base.</li>
          <li><strong>No franchise tax for LLCs:</strong> Unlike some states, Florida does not impose a separate franchise tax on LLCs (though there is a corporate income tax on C-corps).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Steps -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Steps to Form Your Florida LLC</h2>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-8">

        <!-- Step 1 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">1</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Choose a Name for Your Florida LLC</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Your LLC name must be distinguishable from other entities registered in Florida. It must include "Limited Liability Company," "LLC," or "L.L.C."
            </p>
            <p>
              Search for name availability at <a href="https://dos.fl.gov/sunbiz/search/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">sunbiz.org</a>. Florida does not offer a formal name reservation for LLCs, so it is best to file your Articles of Organization promptly after confirming your name is available.
            </p>
            <p>
              You may also want to register a fictitious name (DBA) if you plan to do business under a name different from your LLC's legal name. This is filed with the Florida Division of Corporations.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 2 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">2</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Appoint a Registered Agent</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Every Florida LLC must designate a registered agent with a physical street address in Florida. The registered agent receives legal documents and official state correspondence on behalf of your LLC.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can act as your own registered agent or appoint a professional registered agent service. A professional service offers privacy (their address appears on public filings instead of yours) and ensures someone is always available to accept important documents.
            </p>
            <p>
              Many of our <a href="/best-llc-services/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">recommended LLC formation services</a> include registered agent service with formation.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 3 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">3</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">File Articles of Organization</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              File your Articles of Organization with the Florida Division of Corporations through the <a href="https://dos.fl.gov/sunbiz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">sunbiz.org</a> website. The filing fee is <strong>$125</strong>.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Information required on the form:</strong></p>
            <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-1">
              <li>LLC name</li>
              <li>Principal office address</li>
              <li>Mailing address</li>
              <li>Registered agent name and address</li>
              <li>Name and address of each LLC manager or managing member</li>
              <li>Effective date (can be the filing date or a future date)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Online filings are generally processed within a few business days. You will receive a confirmation from the Division of Corporations once your LLC is officially formed.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 4 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">4</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Create an Operating Agreement</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Florida does not require LLCs to have an operating agreement, but it is highly recommended. This document establishes ownership percentages, member rights and responsibilities, management structure, profit distribution, and procedures for adding or removing members.
            </p>
            <p>
              Having an operating agreement protects your personal liability by clearly separating the LLC as its own entity. It also prevents disputes between members by establishing clear rules in advance.
            </p>
            <p>
              For more details, see our <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">operating agreement guide</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Step 5 -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
            <span class="flex h-10 w-10 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-[#1e3a5f] to-[#0d9488] text-sm font-bold text-white">5</span>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900">Get an EIN</h3>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">
            <p>
              Apply for a free Employer Identification Number from the IRS. You need an EIN to open a business bank account, hire employees, and file taxes. The application is free and takes just a few minutes online at irs.gov.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Annual Report -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Florida Annual Report</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          Florida requires every LLC to file an annual report between January 1 and May 1 each year. The filing fee is <strong>$138.75</strong> (as of our last review). If you miss the deadline, a late fee of $400 is added, and failure to file can result in your LLC being administratively dissolved.
        </p>
        <p>
          The annual report is filed online through sunbiz.org and primarily serves to update or confirm your LLC's information, including the registered agent, principal address, and member or manager details. Even if nothing has changed, you must still file the report to keep your LLC in good standing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Florida will send email reminders before the deadline if you have an email address on file. However, it is wise to set your own calendar reminder since failure to file has severe consequences. If your LLC is administratively dissolved for failure to file, you can reinstate it, but you will need to pay all past-due annual reports, late fees, and a reinstatement fee.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
          Annual report fees may change. Check the current fee at <a href="https://dos.fl.gov/sunbiz/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-teal-700 underline hover:text-teal-900">sunbiz.org</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Costs Breakdown -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Florida LLC Costs Breakdown</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Here is a detailed look at all the fees associated with forming and maintaining a Florida LLC:</p>
        <div class="mt-4 overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="min-w-full border border-gray-200 text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-gray-50">
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Fee</th>
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Cost</th>
                <th class="border-b border-gray-200 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-900">Frequency</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Articles of Organization</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$125</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Registered Agent Designation</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$25 (included in filing)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Registered Agent Service</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$0 - $299/year</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual Report</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$138.75</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Annual (Jan 1 - May 1)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Late Annual Report</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$400 additional</td><td class="px-4 py-3">If filed after May 1</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">EIN (Federal Tax ID)</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Free</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Fictitious Name (DBA) Registration</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$50</td><td class="px-4 py-3">One-time</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certified Copy of Articles</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$30</td><td class="px-4 py-3">As needed</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Certificate of Good Standing</td><td class="px-4 py-3">$5</td><td class="px-4 py-3">As needed</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Many <a href="/best-llc-services/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">LLC formation services</a> offer Florida packages that include the Articles of Organization filing, registered agent service, and operating agreement templates, often for $0 to $299 plus the state fee.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Tax Considerations -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Florida LLC Tax Considerations</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">No Personal State Income Tax</h3>
        <p>
          Florida is one of only a handful of states with no personal income tax. This is a major advantage for LLC members, since LLC income passes through to members' personal tax returns. In Florida, you will not owe any state income tax on that pass-through income, keeping more of your earnings compared to states like California or New York where state income tax rates can exceed 10%.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Federal Income Tax</h3>
        <p>
          Your Florida LLC is still subject to federal income tax. Single-member LLCs report income on Schedule C of Form 1040, and multi-member LLCs file a partnership return (Form 1065). You can also elect S-Corp or C-Corp taxation if beneficial. The lack of state income tax does not affect your federal tax obligations.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Florida Corporate Income Tax</h3>
        <p>
          Florida does impose a corporate income tax, but this applies to C-Corporations, not to LLCs taxed as pass-through entities. If you elect to have your LLC taxed as a C-Corp, the Florida corporate income tax rate is 5.5% on income above $50,000 (as of our last review). Most LLCs taxed as sole proprietorships, partnerships, or S-Corps are not affected.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Sales and Use Tax</h3>
        <p>
          Florida imposes a 6% state sales tax on most tangible personal property and some services. Counties may add a discretionary surtax of 0.5% to 1.5%, bringing the total rate to between 6% and 7.5% depending on location. If your LLC sells taxable goods or services, you must register for a sales tax certificate with the Florida Department of Revenue, collect tax from customers, and remit it on the required schedule.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Self-Employment Tax</h3>
        <p>
          LLC members who actively participate in the business owe federal self-employment tax at 15.3% on net earnings. This is a federal obligation that applies regardless of state. If your LLC earns significant income, consider consulting a tax professional about whether S-Corp election might reduce your overall tax burden.
        </p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Reemployment Tax (Unemployment Tax)</h3>
        <p>
          If your Florida LLC hires employees, you will need to pay reemployment tax (Florida's version of unemployment insurance tax). The rate varies based on your industry and claims history. Register with the Florida Department of Revenue when you hire your first employee.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Foreign LLC Registration -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Registering a Foreign LLC in Florida</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          If your LLC was formed in another state but you conduct business in Florida, you must register as a foreign LLC with the Florida Division of Corporations. You file an Application by Foreign LLC on the sunbiz.org website. The filing fee is $125, the same as domestic LLC formation.
        </p>
        <p>
          You will need to provide a Certificate of Existence (or Certificate of Good Standing) from your home state, designate a Florida registered agent, and provide the names and addresses of your LLC's managers or managing members.
        </p>
        <p>
          Activities that generally require foreign LLC registration in Florida include maintaining an office, having employees in the state, owning real property, or conducting regular business transactions within Florida. Transacting business without registering can result in fines, back fees, and the inability to use Florida courts to enforce your contracts.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Timeline -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">How Long Does It Take to Form a Florida LLC?</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Florida is known for relatively fast LLC processing times:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Online filing:</strong> Typically processed within one to three business days. Florida's sunbiz.org system is efficient and user-friendly.</li>
          <li><strong>Mail filing:</strong> Can take one to two weeks depending on volume at the Division of Corporations.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a formation service:</strong> Services like <a href="/reviews/zenbusiness/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">ZenBusiness</a> or <a href="/reviews/northwest-registered-agent/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">Northwest Registered Agent</a> typically submit filings the same day or next business day and handle the entire process for you.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          After your Articles of Organization are approved, you can immediately obtain your EIN from the IRS (instant online) and open a business bank account. The entire process from filing to operating can often be completed within a week.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Common Mistakes -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Common Mistakes When Forming a Florida LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Missing the annual report deadline:</strong> The $400 late fee is steep, and continued failure to file leads to administrative dissolution. Set reminders for the January 1 through May 1 window.</li>
          <li><strong>Not having an operating agreement:</strong> While Florida does not require one, operating without a written agreement invites disputes and weakens your liability protection. See our <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">guide to LLC operating agreements</a> for what to include.</li>
          <li><strong>Mixing personal and business finances:</strong> This is the most common way business owners lose LLC liability protection. Open a dedicated business bank account and never use it for personal expenses.</li>
          <li><strong>Filing the name too late:</strong> Florida does not offer formal name reservations for LLCs. If you find an available name, file your Articles of Organization promptly before someone else takes it.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to register for sales tax:</strong> If you sell taxable goods or services in Florida, you must have a sales tax certificate before making your first sale. Selling without one can result in penalties and back taxes.</li>
          <li><strong>Not obtaining local permits:</strong> Many Florida counties and cities require separate business licenses, occupational licenses, or zoning permits. Check with your local county and municipality.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a P.O. Box for the registered agent:</strong> Florida requires a physical street address for the registered agent. A P.O. Box will be rejected.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Industry Considerations -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Industry-Specific Considerations in Florida</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Florida's diverse economy means LLC requirements can vary by industry:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Real estate:</strong> Florida is one of the top states for real estate investment. Many investors use LLCs to hold rental properties for liability protection. Florida allows Series LLCs, which can be useful for holding multiple properties under one umbrella entity.</li>
          <li><strong>Tourism and hospitality:</strong> Restaurants, hotels, vacation rentals, and tour companies may need additional permits from the Florida Department of Business and Professional Regulation (DBPR) and local tourism boards.</li>
          <li><strong>Construction:</strong> Florida requires contractor licensing through the DBPR. General contractors, roofing contractors, and other specialty trades need specific state licenses in addition to their LLC formation.</li>
          <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Medical professionals in Florida may need to form a Professional LLC (PLLC) rather than a standard LLC. Additional licensing through the Florida Department of Health is required.</li>
          <li><strong>E-commerce:</strong> Florida's lack of personal income tax makes it attractive for online businesses. However, you must still collect sales tax on sales to Florida customers and comply with economic nexus rules for out-of-state sales.</li>
          <li><strong>Marine and boating:</strong> Given Florida's extensive coastline, marine businesses (charter companies, boat sales, marinas) have specific state and federal licensing requirements beyond the basic LLC formation.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Advantages and Disadvantages -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Advantages and Disadvantages of a Florida LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900">Advantages</h3>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li>No personal state income tax means LLC members keep more of their pass-through profits.</li>
          <li>No separate franchise tax for LLCs (unlike Texas or California).</li>
          <li>Affordable $125 filing fee and straightforward online filing through sunbiz.org.</li>
          <li>Fast processing times, often one to three business days for online filings.</li>
          <li>Large and growing consumer market with over 22 million residents and a massive tourism industry.</li>
          <li>Strong charging order protections for single-member LLCs, providing solid asset protection.</li>
          <li>Favorable homestead exemption that protects your primary residence from most creditors.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 mt-6">Disadvantages</h3>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li>The $138.75 annual report fee is required every year with a severe $400 late penalty.</li>
          <li>Manager and member names and addresses are publicly available through sunbiz.org, offering less privacy than states like Delaware or Wyoming.</li>
          <li>Florida's property insurance costs can be very high, particularly in hurricane-prone areas, which impacts businesses that own real property.</li>
          <li>No formal name reservation process for LLCs means you must file quickly to secure your chosen name.</li>
          <li>Florida's regulatory environment for certain industries (construction, healthcare) can be complex.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- After Formation -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">After You Form Your Florida LLC</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
        <p>Once your Florida LLC is approved, complete these essential steps:</p>
        <ul class="ml-6 list-disc space-y-2">
          <li><strong>Get your EIN from the IRS:</strong> Apply online at irs.gov. It is free and instant during business hours.</li>
          <li><strong>Open a business bank account:</strong> Maintain separation between personal and business finances. Bring your Articles of Organization, EIN confirmation letter, and photo ID.</li>
          <li><strong>Create your operating agreement:</strong> Draft and sign a comprehensive <a href="/learn/llc-operating-agreement/" class="text-teal-700 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-teal-900">operating agreement</a> with all members.</li>
          <li><strong>Get necessary licenses and permits:</strong> Check with your county and city for local business license requirements. Florida requires specific licenses for many regulated industries through the DBPR.</li>
          <li><strong>Register for sales tax:</strong> If you sell taxable goods or services, register with the Florida Department of Revenue for a sales tax certificate before you begin selling.</li>
          <li><strong>Set up accounting and bookkeeping:</strong> Implement a system to track income, expenses, and sales tax from day one.</li>
          <li><strong>Consider business insurance:</strong> General liability, professional liability, and property insurance are common needs depending on your business type and location.</li>
          <li><strong>Mark your annual report deadline:</strong> Set calendar reminders for the January 1 to May 1 annual report filing window. Missing this deadline costs an extra $400.</li>
          <li><strong>Register a fictitious name if needed:</strong> If you plan to operate under a name other than your LLC's legal name, file a fictitious name registration with the Division of Corporations ($50 fee).</li>
          <li><strong>Build business credit:</strong> Open a business credit card, establish vendor accounts, and maintain timely payments to build your LLC's credit profile.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 sm:text-3xl">Frequently Asked Questions About Florida LLCs</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-6">
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">How much does it cost to start an LLC in Florida?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">The Articles of Organization filing fee is $125. Beyond that, you will need to budget for the annual report ($138.75 per year), a registered agent service ($0-$299 per year if using a professional), and any optional formation service fees. In the first year, expect to spend about $265 to $425 in required state fees.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Does Florida have a franchise tax for LLCs?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">No. Florida does not impose a separate franchise tax on LLCs. The primary ongoing state cost is the $138.75 annual report fee. Florida does have a corporate income tax, but it applies to C-Corporations, not to LLCs taxed as pass-through entities.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Do I need to live in Florida to form a Florida LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">No. Anyone can form a Florida LLC regardless of where they live. You will need a registered agent with a physical street address in Florida. If you do not live in the state, a professional registered agent service is the simplest solution.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What happens if I miss the annual report deadline?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">If you file your annual report after May 1, a $400 late fee is added to the $138.75 filing fee. If you do not file at all by the third Friday in September, your LLC will be administratively dissolved. You can reinstate it, but you will owe all back annual reports, late fees, and a reinstatement fee.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Can I reserve an LLC name in Florida?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Florida does not offer a formal name reservation for LLCs. Once you find an available name on sunbiz.org, it is best to file your Articles of Organization as soon as possible to secure it. You can also file a fictitious name (DBA) registration for $50 if you want to operate under a different name.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">How long does it take to get a Florida LLC approved?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Online filings through sunbiz.org are typically processed within one to three business days. Mail filings may take one to two weeks. Using a formation service can simplify the process since they prepare and submit everything on your behalf, often on the same business day.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Is Florida a good state for a single-member LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Yes. Florida provides strong charging order protections for single-member LLCs, which means creditors generally cannot seize your LLC membership interest to satisfy personal debts. Combined with no state income tax, Florida is considered one of the best states for single-member LLC asset protection.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Do I need a business license in Florida?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Florida does not have a single statewide general business license. However, most counties and cities require local business licenses or tax receipts. Additionally, many regulated professions require specific state licenses from the Department of Business and Professional Regulation. Check with both your local government and state regulatory body for your industry.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">Can a Florida LLC elect S-Corp taxation?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Yes. A Florida LLC can elect S-Corp taxation by filing IRS Form 2553. Since Florida has no personal income tax, the primary benefit of S-Corp election in Florida is reducing your federal self-employment tax by splitting income between salary and distributions. Consult a tax professional to determine if this makes sense for your situation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-gray-900">What is a Florida Series LLC?</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700">Florida allows the formation of Series LLCs, which contain multiple "series" or cells within a single LLC. Each series can hold separate assets and have separate members, with liability isolated between series. This structure is popular among real estate investors who hold multiple properties, as it can be more cost-effective than forming a separate LLC for each property.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

